ChronicCopilot: Project Proposal & Architecture Overview
1. Introduction: The Vision and The Problem
What is this project? ChronicCopilot is an AI-driven backend architecture designed to safely monitor and manage patients with chronic diseases (like diabetes and hypertension) from their homes. It acts as an automated, highly secure bridge between a patient's wearable devices and their doctor's hospital system.

The Problem It Solves: Currently, healthcare apps and remote patient monitoring (RPM) systems suffer from three major failures:

The "Dumb Alarm" Problem (Alert Fatigue): Standard apps just beep when a single number (like blood pressure) goes too high. This creates thousands of false alarms that nurses ignore.
The "Reckless AI" Problem (Hallucination): Newer AI systems (like raw ChatGPT) can give patients dangerous, unverified medical advice because they want to be "helpful."
The "Missing Money" Problem (Billing Audit): Hospitals lose out on thousands of dollars because they cannot easily prove to insurance companies (like Medicare) exactly how many minutes they spent actively monitoring the patient's data.

The Solution & Accomplishment: ChronicCopilot solves these by introducing a closed-loop orchestration system. It ingests data from wearables, uses a strict mathematical model to find real anomalies, asks an AI for a personalized patient nudge, but forces that AI through hard-coded safety guardrails before doing anything. Finally, it formats the alert in standard medical coding (FHIR) and automatically logs the system usage time for hospital billing.


2. System Architecture: How It Works & Why
This section breaks down the technical flow of the system. For each step, the engineering decision is justified by recent academic literature to prove its viability.
