1. Data Ingestion
Multimodal Data Stream (FastAPI)
Instead of just looking at one number (like blood sugar), the system looks at the whole picture simultaneously: wearables, recent lab results, and whether the patient took their meds today.
Proven By [1], [5], [11]: Research shows that combining wearable data with medication adherence logs significantly improves predictive accuracy (up to 84% in recent models) compared to isolated metrics.
2. Storage
Time-Series Database (PostgreSQL)
Medical wearables send data every few minutes. Standard databases crash under this load, so we use an optimized time-series structure to store the data without lag.
Proven By [8]: Scalable time-series architectures are empirically required to handle the high-frequency IoT data generated by Continuous Glucose Monitors without system latency.
3. The "Math Brain"
Statistical Anomaly Detector (scikit-learn)
A mathematical algorithm (Isolation Forest) establishes what is "normal" for this specific patient. It only flags data if it severely breaks the patient's personal baseline, reducing false alarms.
Proven By [6], [9]: Trajectory-based escalation and dynamic baselines are proven to heavily mitigate "alert fatigue," preventing nurses from ignoring critical system warnings.
4. The "Talking Brain"
Tool-Augmented LLM (FastMCP & Groq/Claude API)
When an anomaly is found, a Large Language Model (LLM) is used to read the data and draft a personalized, empathetic message to the patient (e.g., reminding them to eat).
Proven By [10]: Using LLMs constrained by external tools (like checking a database via MCP) significantly reduces errors compared to letting the AI rely on its own knowledge.
5. The Safety Net
Deterministic Guardrails (Python Logic)
Crucial Step: Before the AI's message is sent, strict if/else coding rules double-check it against medical limits. If the AI suggests a dangerous dose, the system blocks it.
Proven By [2], [7]: Studies show AI models suffer from "sycophancy" (agreeing with bad logic to please users) and hallucinate 8-15% of the time in medical contexts. Hard guardrails are mandatory for safety.
6. Hospital Handoff
FHIR Adapter & Reimbursement Audit
If an alert needs a doctor, the system formats it into standard medical JSON (HL7 FHIR). Simultaneously, a background database table logs the exact minutes the system processed the data so the hospital can legally bill for the work.
Proven By [3], [12]: FHIR integration is the industry standard for interoperability, and automated time-tracking systems are identified as the primary solution to overcoming the administrative burden of RPM billing audits.



3. Proof of Concept (MVP) Strategy
To build this for a university project without violating patient privacy or requiring massive computing power, the project will utilize the following stack:

Simulated Data: We will write Python scripts to generate synthetic heart rate and continuous glucose data. No real human data will be used, completely bypassing HIPAA privacy regulations.
Open-Source Math: The anomaly detection will run on standard, free Python libraries (scikit-learn).
Cloud API Reasoning: The LLM reasoning layer will be powered by developer-tier APIs (like Groq or Anthropic Claude) integrated via the open-source Model Context Protocol (MCP), removing the need for expensive local GPU hardware.
Standardized Backend: The core routing will be built in Python using FastAPI, running alongside a PostgreSQL database to mimic a real-world enterprise backend.


4. Why This is a High-Value Academic Project
This project does not attempt to invent a new machine learning algorithm, as that space is highly saturated. Instead, the novelty lies in System Orchestration.

By wiring together isolated technologies (predictive math, generative AI, and medical billing standards) and enforcing a strict Hybrid Safety Layer, this architecture fills a clearly identified gap in current medical literature. It proves that software engineers can constrain unpredictable AI models to build safe, reimbursement-aware clinical tools.


